      So, Elon
   =20
 =20
I guess it is worth saying that Elon Musk does not own Twitter Inc. He did =
not buy Twitter Inc. yesterday for $54.20 per share in cash. He did=C2=A0si=
gn an agreement yesterday to buy Twitter for $54.20 in cash. That is a big =
step! It means=C2=A0that he probably=C2=A0will=C2=A0end up owning Twitter w=
ithin a few months or so. (The deal =E2=80=9Cis expected to close in 2022=
=E2=80=9D; it might take  up to six months.) But he does not own it yet.So,=
 for instance, he cannot change anything about Twitter yet; he can=E2=80=99=
t change moderation policies or open-source the algorithm or bring back Don=
ald Trump, or whatever you are excited or worried about,=C2=A0until the dea=
l closes.=C2=A0Employees who are unhappy about Musk=E2=80=99s plans for Twi=
tter can quit, but he can=E2=80=99t fire them yet. Reuters notes:Bret Taylo=
r, chair of Twitter's board of directors, aimed to reassure employees that =
the agreement with Musk prioritized "operating continuity" until the deal w=
as closed."I think we feel very comfortable that (the deal) gives this team=
 the ability to continue to make the company successful in between signing =
and closing the transaction," Taylor said.On that same employee call,=C2=A0=
CEO Parag Agrawal said =E2=80=9COnce the deal closes, we don't know which d=
irection the platform will go.=E2=80=9D Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0Agrawal and =
his team and the board =E2=80=94=C2=A0are in charge of Twitter from now unt=
il the deal closes, with little or no meddling by Musk,  and they=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Ctold employees on Monday that the social network will keep operating =
as usual=E2=80=9D until the closing. After the deal closes, it=E2=80=99s al=
l Musk.Why does it take so long? Well, some things need to happen between n=
ow and when the deal closes. Most notably, Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders h=
ave to vote on the deal. Twitter will have to write a proxy statement expla=
ining the deal, run it by the Securities and Exchange Commission, send it t=
o shareholders and give=C2=A0them some time to read it before voting; this =
can take months. Also there are regulatory approvals =E2=80=94=C2=A0under a=
ntitrust laws, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Twitter and Musk need to get before=
 closing the deal. Also when the deal closes Elon Musk will need to have ab=
out $46=C2=A0billion in cash[1]; he has agreements =E2=80=94=C2=A0with bank=
s and with himself =E2=80=94=C2=A0to get the cash, but actually getting it =
can take time.=C2=A0In the next couple of days, Twitter will publicly file =
its merger agreement with Musk, laying out what needs to happen between sig=
ning and closing. (I was sort of expecting it to be filed by now, but techn=
ically they get four days=C2=A0and they have been busy; I suppose we will t=
alk about it when it is filed.)And then it will get to work on the proxy st=
atement, which will probably be filed within a few weeks. The proxy will be=
 interesting. One interesting part will be the =E2=80=9CBackground of the M=
erger=E2=80=9D section, describing the history of Musk=E2=80=99s negotiatio=
ns with Twitter, Twitter=E2=80=99s consideration of his offer, Twitter=E2=
=80=99s efforts to find other bidders, etc. Probably some mention will be m=
ade of various tweets. Probably the lawyers will have to finesse a bit how =
Musk characterized his Twitter stake as a passive investment with no intent=
ion to change control of the company on April 4, and made a takeover offer =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0saying that =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s simply=C2=A0not a good inv=
estment without the changes that need to be made=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0ni=
ne days later. It has been a busy month, for Elon Musk and Twitter, and the=
 proxy statement will detail how they negotiated this deal and also how lit=
tle their lawyers slept.Another interesting section will be the =E2=80=9COp=
inion of Twitter=E2=80=99s Financial Advisers,=E2=80=9D which will describe=
 the fairness opinion that Twitter=E2=80=99s board got from its bankers con=
cluding that Musk=E2=80=99s price of $54.20 per share is fair to Twitter=E2=
=80=99s shareholders. I think it probably was not=C2=A0too=C2=A0hard for th=
e banks to reach that conclusion. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Michelle Davis and L=
iana Baker report:The third catalyst that led to a deal was the role of the=
 price, $54.20, and how it compared with Twitter=E2=80=99s own growth prosp=
ects. The company=E2=80=99s advisers, which included Goldman Sachs Group In=
c. and JPMorgan Chase & Co., did a valuation analysis and presented it to t=
he board last Friday, one of the people said. Musk=E2=80=99s camp didn=E2=
=80=99t get a look at those materials, though, given the decision to bypass=
 reviewing Twitter=E2=80=99s books.Twitter=E2=80=99s shares were trading we=
ll below Musk=E2=80=99s bid, with the stock closing at $47.08 the previous =
day, and far from their $70-plus highs of a year earlier. But the question =
was whether the stock could recover without taking the deal. The analysis d=
idn=E2=80=99t paint an optimistic picture.=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s board con=
cluded from the presentation that, based on where peers were trading, its s=
hares wouldn=E2=80=99t reach Musk=E2=80=99s bid price anytime soon.I  joked=
 yesterday that the bankers would have to =E2=80=9Ctweak the model until it=
 makes a horrible clattering noise and bolts start popping off=E2=80=9D to =
get up to a $54.20 valuation for Twitter, and that was probably too harsh, =
but the proxy statement will give you some sense of (1) Twitter=E2=80=99s m=
anagement projections for its business for the next few years and (2) what =
its bankers think the company is worth, given those projections. The short =
answer will be =E2=80=9Cless than $54.20 per share.=E2=80=9DSo they=E2=80=
=99ll put out the proxy, they=E2=80=99ll schedule a meeting, they=E2=80=99l=
l work to line up financing and regulatory approvals, there=E2=80=99ll be a=
 shareholder vote; a lot has to happen before this deal closes.=C2=A0Will i=
t close? Sure, yeah, probably; the stock trading apparently implies an 84% =
probability that the merger closes.[2] But=C2=A0let=E2=80=99s take a quick =
tour of what can go wrong, just in case.First: Musk could change his mind.=
=C2=A0This is, you know, frowned upon in high-level mergers and acquisition=
s, but he is Elon Musk and he is not necessarily beholden to traditional ru=
