At CNBC, Alex Sherman has a fascinating account of the demise of CNN+, the =
paid streaming service that CNN launched and then almost immediately abando=
ned. In Sherman=E2=80=99s telling, CNN+ is basically a story of mergers and=
 acquisitions gone wrong. CNN decided to launch CNN+ when it was part of Wa=
rnerMedia, which was itself part of AT&T Inc.:WarnerMedia executives had a =
plan to meet their goal: They would use HBO Max, CNN.com and CNN=E2=80=99s =
linear channel as a constant marketing presence =E2=80=93 a =E2=80=9Cfunnel=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 to push subscribers. The strategy was to launch CNN+ in=
 the beginning of this year and then bundle it with HBO Max in September. T=
his =E2=80=9Cwould you like fries with that=E2=80=9D approach for the milli=
ons of subscribers that sign up for HBO Max (HBO and HBO Max had 3 million =
new net adds last quarter) would ultimately lead to a robust, globally scal=
ed news service.And a CNN executive named Andrew Morse was put in charge of=
 it. But then AT&T decided to sell WarnerMedia to Discovery Inc. (Technical=
ly, to do a =E2=80=9Creverse Morris Trust=E2=80=9D=C2=A0spinoff of WarnerMe=
dia and merge it with Discovery.) And Discovery=E2=80=99s CEO, David Zaslav=
, was not into CNN+:He wanted to push together HBO Max and Discovery+ and u=
se news and live sports from WarnerMedia to make the streaming bundle even =
more attractive. The collection of assets, he thought, could take on Netfli=
x as a global streaming behemoth. CNN will ultimately be a tab within the l=
arger HBO Max-Discovery+ service.That made the existence of CNN+ antithetic=
al to his strategy. ...CNN+ would be a sideshow niche product. Even if it s=
howed growth, taking subscribers away from the larger bundle with the promi=
se of a cheaper option in CNN+ would hurt Warner Bros. Discovery and repres=
ent a waste of resources.Fine. Except that due to antitrust regulation =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0which frowns upon executives at big competing companies coordin=
ating with each other, even if one is about to buy the other =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0Zaslav and Morse couldn=E2=80=99t talk to each other:In the weeks before=
 the launch, Morse began begging [Warner CEO Jason]=C2=A0Kilar and other AT=
&T executives to see if there was a way he could speak with the Discovery l=
eaders. Staffers described it as Morse =E2=80=9Cshouting from the rooftops=
=E2=80=9D for a meeting.CNBC reported the day after [CNN head Jeff] Zucker =
left in February that Discovery wasn=E2=80=99t enamored with CNN+ and disag=
reed with the strategy. The next day, Zaslav told CNBC he =E2=80=9Chadn=E2=
=80=99t gotten a business review on what CNN+ is going to be and how it=E2=
=80=99s going to be offered,=E2=80=9D which was an ominous statement for it=
s future.Morse wanted to find out directly from Discovery what Zaslav wante=
d. But AT&T told CNN=E2=80=99s team it couldn=E2=80=99t have any discussion=
s with Discovery because of so-called gun-jumping laws which don=E2=80=99t =
allow the two sides to discuss future strategy until a merger closes. Kilar=
 never spoke with Zaslav about CNN+, and he wasn=E2=80=99t going to make de=
cisions about what he thought was best for CNN+ based on media reports.Zasl=
av did meet with CNN executives in early March in a so-called =E2=80=9Cparl=
or=E2=80=9D meeting with Michael Bass, Amy Entelis, and Ken Jautz, who were=
 running CNN after Zucker left, as first reported by Puck=E2=80=99s Dylan B=
yers. In that meeting, Zaslav inquired about CNN+ and its go-forward strate=
gy, but lawyers in attendance told him he wasn=E2=80=99t allowed ask about =
it.CNN had been pushing to launch CNN+ in early 2022, and had expected the =
AT&T deal to close in the middle of 2022. =E2=80=9CThat would give the serv=
ice a few months of breathing space before Zaslav=E2=80=99s leadership team=
 took over for Kilar.=E2=80=9D But then the deal closed faster than expecte=
d, and CNN+ took longer to build than expected, which =E2=80=9Cput the laun=
ch of CNN+ just weeks before the merger=E2=80=99s close date.=E2=80=9D And =
because Morse couldn=E2=80=99t talk to his imminent future bosses, he just =
went ahead and launched. And then the merger closed, and =E2=80=9Cat 8 a.m.=
 ET on April 11 =E2=80=94 the first day Warner Bros. Discovery began tradin=
g as a combined company =E2=80=94 [Discovery executives] told Morse and his=
 team that CNN+=E2=80=99s marketing budget was immediately going to zero.=
=E2=80=9D Ten days later, CNN+ was dead.One possible lesson here is, like, =
don=E2=80=99t hire hundreds of people to rush to launch a new product just =
before a merger closes, on the theory that if the people are already there =
and the product already exists then the acquirer will have no choice but to=
 keep them around. That is not how it works! If you are building content mo=
deration tools at Twitter you might ponder that lesson.
